\section{Data collection}
The study comprehended a series of monitoring events from April 2025 to October 2025. Sampling sessions were held with a monthly frequency. Data recording was divided into two parts: the information on the flowering flora (identities of flowering plant species and floral cover), and the information on interactions within insects and flowers. The choice of the monitoring days was based on relative meteorological conditions (to choose days with suitable conditions for insect flight) and surveyors availability. Additionally, fieldwork hours were adjusted to avoid adverse weather conditions, including rain, excessive wind, extreme cold, or heat. Monitoring operations were held in the range between 9 a.m. and 3 p.m., temperature, relative humidity, wind speed, and cloud cover were recorded for each monitoring day.

Following the guidelines of \cite{LIFE4Pollinators}, suitable weather conditions for insect flight and for flower opening comprehend temperature between 15°C and 35°C, less than 50\% cloud cover, absence of rain and wind speed below 15 $\frac{\text{km}}{\text{h}}$, less than 4 on the Beaufort scale. This is a scale that explains how wind speed can be estimated by observing wind affecting objects in the environment, from 0 (calm), to 12 (hurricane), force 4 is described as moderate breeze that raises dust and loose paper, small branches are moved \parencite{meadenComparingTheoreticalVersions2007}. 

The protocol was the exact same for each of the 5 above mentioned areas.
 

\subsection{Flowering flora}

A flora of the flowering plants of the area was elaborated listing all species found on site, each month. It comprehends species in the above mentioned areas and the surroundings. Some were identified directly on site but when field taxonomic identification was not possible, samples were collected, identified in the laboratory, and dried to create a reference sample preserved at the University of Bologna Herbarium. Identification was carried out mainly thanks to dichotomous keys in Pignatti’s “Flora D’Italia”  \parencite{pignattiFloraDItalia1982}. 


\subsection{Floral cover}

To get the flower abundance data 4 plots of 1 square meter were placed in each site along the transect, each month (Figure \ref{fig:plotimage}). Locus-Map, a multi-functional navigation application was used to record coordinates and time and to upload photos of the plot. The placing of these plots was randomized for it to be representative of the flower diversity of the area. In each plot flower units and plant species were registered together with the geographic coordinates, climatic conditions, floral shape, date and time. 

In each quadrant, flowering plants were identified to the species level, and functional flower pollination units were counted (we considered single flower, flower head or inflorescence depending on the association of each specie's flowering). 

The floral shape of each specie was recognized on field based on the “Illustrated guide of floral shapes” elaborated from  \cite{faegriPrinciplesPollinationEcology2013}. 

