\subsection{Pollination networks}
Interaction data was collected through a transect for each site.
The transects are fixed, same positioning every month, they are 50 m long and 2 m wide. They are placed within the above-mentioned areas. The placing was chosen for it to be representative of the area and to capture maximum diversity within it. Because of this it did not necessarily follow a straight line, it followed diversity gradients depending on the site.

During these transects every interaction between a visiting insect and a flower is registered on a paper sheet on the field. An entomological net is used while walking the transect, during an exact 15-minute time slot. Only insects directly interacting with flowers are caught, time is stopped during visitors sample collection and handling. These are kept in a Falcon tube in an ice bag to avoid multiple counting of the same individual. After finishing the sampling, surveyors identified the collected insects and released them. Visitors were identified at morpho-genus level on field and for bees it was possible to reach the genus thanks to the presence of an expert taxonomist Dr. Laura Bortolotti. The functional groups considered here are those of bees, wasps, bee flies, moths, butterflies, hoverflies, and beetles.


%Order Hymenoptera: bees, wasps

%Order Lepidoptera: butterflies, moths

%Order Diptera: bee flies, hoverflies 

%Order Coleoptera: beetles

Exception to the catch-and-release can be made for individuals that could not be confidently assigned to any morpho-genus. In this case, individuals are killed, placed in Falcon tubes, with annotations including capture ID number, plant species, site acronym, and date. Then they are transferred to the laboratory freezer at –2°C for at least two days and subsequently prepared for taxonomic identification under a stereo-microscope. All specimens are conserved at the Laboratory of Plant Reproductive Ecology, Department of Biological, Geological and Environmental Sciences, University of Bologna.

