\section{Data analysis}


\subsection{Flowering plant communities' diversity}
For Flowering plant communities' diversity analysis the dataset of the  floral cover was used, which contained the information got form the plots, the abundances of pollination units per specie. The indices taken into account for describing diversity across habitats and months were: Species richness (\(S\)), Shannon diversity (\(H'\)), Simpson dominance (\(D\)) and Pielou's evenness (\(J'\)), all found in Table \ref{tab:diversity_metrics}. These metrics were obtained using software R \parencite{rcoreteamLanguageEnvironmentStatistical2023} and package "vegan" \parencite{oksanenVeganCommunityEcology2025}. Graphs were created by package "ggplot2" \parencite{wickhamGgplot2CreateElegant2025}. 
Statistical analysis were also obtained using R, Kruskal-wallis test was run to test the differences within abundances (package "stats", \cite{rcoreteamStatsStatisticalCalculations}) while Hutchinson t-test (package "ecolTest", \cite{salinasEcolTestCommunityEcology2021}) was run to test the difference within the Shannon-Weiner diversity indeces. 


\begin{table}[ht!]
	\centering
	\caption{Metrics used to describe diversity in the flowering plant community.}
	\label{tab:diversity_metrics}
	\begin{tabular}{|p{3cm}|p{4cm}|p{4cm}|p{3cm}|}
		\hline
		\textbf{Metric} & \textbf{Ecological meaning} & \textbf{Formula} & \textbf{Range \& Interpretation} \\
		\hline
		Species richness (\(S\)) & Number of flowering plant species present in the community. & \[ S = \sum_{i=1}^{N} I_i \] & \(1-N\), increasing values = more species present \\
		\hline
		Shannon diversity (\(H'\)) & Species diversity; integrates richness and evenness of abundances. & \[ H' = -\sum_{i=1}^{S} p_i \ln(p_i) \] & \(0-\ln(S)\), increasing values = higher diversity \\
		\hline
		Simpson dominance (\(D\)) & Probability that two randomly selected individuals belong to the same species. & \[ D = \sum_{i=1}^{S} p_i^2 \] & \(0-1\), increasing values = higher dominance \\
		\hline
		Pielou's evenness (\(J'\)) & Uniformity in the distribution of abundances among species. & \[ J' = \frac{H'}{\ln(S)} \] & \(0-1\), increasing values = more even distribution \\
		\hline
	\end{tabular}
\end{table}





\subsection{Pollination networks' diversity}
For pollination networks' diversity the dataset of the registered interaction was used, which contained the information got from the transects. The indices taken into account for describing network diversity across habitats and months were selected for representing distinct ecological dimensions of the network. These are: Species richness, both at plant level ($S_p$) and at pollinator level ($S_a$), Shannon diversity ($H'$), Pielou's evenness of interactions ($E$), Linkage density ($LD$), Weighted connectance ($C_w$), Network-level specialization ($H_2'$), Nestedness ($NODF$). Robustness ($R$) and Functional complementarity ($FC$) were also computed for the plant community. All are found in Table \ref{tab:network_metrics}. These were all computed with R's package "Bipartite" \parencite{dormannBipartiteVisualisingBipartite2025}
Shannon diversity (also called Shannon–Weiner index) was used to quantify interaction diversity, integrating both richness and evenness of interactions, it better captures the presence of rare interaction links in networks with relatively limited observations per habitat; Simpson’s index, being more influenced by dominant links, adds less information under these sampling conditions and therefore wasn't calculated for the network analysis \parencite{MeasuringConservationSuccess2024}.  

For pollination networks the plotweb function in R's package "bipartite" was used. Result is a weighted quantitative interaction of plants (right column) and pollinators (left column) with an independent abundance.  Each bar represents a taxonomic or functional unit, and the connecting lines indicate observed visitation or pollination events. The plant-pollinator network provides a visual complexity of interactions between plants and pollinators, and shows the specificity of these relationships. It allows identification of which pollinator functional groups and which plant species (or families) are more generalists and which have more specialized roles.

Statistical analysis were obtained using R (R Core Team, 2021), package "vegan" \parencite{oksanenVeganCommunityEcology2025}, to visualize and assess seasonal changes in community composition, we performed a Non-Metric Multidimensional Scaling (NMDS) ordination, a multivariate statistical analysis based on Bray–Curtis dissimilarity. This statistical technique takes a matrix of dissimilarities between samples (in this case, monthly pollination networks) and plots them in a two dimensions space. The algorithm tries to place the samples on the graph so that the distances between points accurately reflect their ecological dissimilarity. 


\begin{table}[ht!]
	\centering
	\caption{Metrics used to describe the diversity and structure of plant--pollinator networks.}
	\label{tab:network_metrics}
	\begin{tabular}{|p{2cm}| p{5.5cm}| p{3.5cm}| p{4cm}|}
		\hline
		\textbf{Metric} & \textbf{Ecological meaning} & \textbf{Formula} & \textbf{Range \& Interpretation} \\
		\hline
		
		Plant richness ($S_p$) &
		Number of flowering plant species involved in at least one pollination interaction. &
		\[
		S_p = \sum_{i=1}^{N_p} I_i
		\]
		&
		$1$–$N_p$, increasing values = more plant species present
		\\
		\hline
		Pollinator richness ($S_a$) &
		Number of pollinator species involved in at least one pollination interaction. &
		\[
		S_a = \sum_{j=1}^{N_a} I_j
		\]
		&
		$1$–$N_a$, increasing values = more pollinator species present
		\\
		\hline
		Shannon diversity of interactions ($H'$) &
		Diversity of plant--pollinator interactions; integrates richness and evenness. &
		\[
		H' = - \sum_{i=1}^{L} p_i \ln(p_i)
		\]
		&
		$0$–$\ln(L)$, increasing values = higher interaction diversity
		\\
		\hline
		Pielou's evenness of interactions ($E$) &
		Uniformity in the distribution of interaction frequencies. &
		\[
		E = \frac{H'}{\ln(L)}
		\]
		&
		$0$–$1$, increasing values = more even distribution of interactions
		\\
		\hline
		Linkage density ($LD$) &
		Average number of links per species, weighted by interaction frequency. &
		\[
		LD = \frac{L}{S_T} \quad \text{or} \quad \frac{\sum w_{ij}}{S_T}
		\]
		&
		$0$–$\infty$, increasing values = more links per species on average
		\\
		\hline
		Weighted connectance ($C_w$) &
		Proportion of realized weighted interactions relative to the maximum possible. &
		\[
		C_w = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{N_p} \sum_{j=1}^{N_a} w_{ij}}{N_p \times N_a}
		\]
		&
		$0$–$1$, increasing values = more interactions realized relative to potential
		\\
		\hline
		Network-level specialization ($H_2'$) &
		Overall degree of specialization of the network. &
		See \cite{bluthgenMeasuringSpecializationSpecies2006}
		&
		$0$–$1$, increasing values = higher network specialization
		\\
		\hline
		Nestedness ($NODF$) &
		Degree to which interactions of specialist species are subsets of generalist species. &
		 See \cite{almeida-netoConsistentMetricNestedness2008}.
		&
		$0$–$100$, increasing values = more hierarchical, nested network structure
		\\
		\hline
		Robustness ($R$) &
		Resilience to species loss; measures the proportion of plant species surviving after sequential removal of pollinator species. &
		See \cite{burgosWhyNestednessMutualistic2007} &
		$0$–$1$, increasing values = higher network stability to species extinctions
		\\
		\hline
		Functional complementarity ($FC$) &
		Degree of niche differentiation; measures how much plant species differ in their interaction patterns (redundancy vs. complementarity). &
		See \cite{bluthgenWhatInteractionNetwork2008} &
		$0$–$\infty$, increasing values = higher functional differentiation among species
		\\
		
		\hline
	\end{tabular}
	
	\vspace{0.2cm}
	\footnotesize
	\textbf{Note:} In interaction-based metrics, $p_i$ represents the proportion of the total interaction frequency corresponding to interaction $i$, $L$ is the total number of observed links, ${S_T}$ is the total number of species, $w_{ij}$ is the interaction frequency between plant species $i$ and pollinator species $j$, $N_p$ is the number of plant species, and $N_a$ is the number of pollinator species. 
\end{table}



